# Python testing practices and guidelines

## Test structure

- Organize tests to mirror source code structure.
- Keep test files focused and well-organized.
- Use clear, descriptive test names following the pattern: `test_[unit][scenario][expected]`.
- Group related tests using pytest classes.
- Use fixtures for common setup and teardown.
- Separate unit tests from integration tests.
- Use markers to categorize tests (`@pytest.mark`).

## Test coverage

- Write tests for all new functionality.
- Include tests for:
  - Happy path scenarios
  - Edge cases and boundary conditions
  - Error conditions and exception handling
  - Input validation
  - Complex business logic
- Aim for comprehensive coverage (target > 80%).
- Use coverage reports to identify gaps.
- Test both sync and async code paths.

## Test quality

- Keep tests independent and isolated.
- Use appropriate test fixtures for reusability.
- Mock external dependencies consistently.
- Use meaningful test data that reflects real scenarios.
- Write deterministic tests (no random data unless controlled and seeded).
- Follow Arrange–Act–Assert.
- Use parametrized tests for multiple scenarios.
- Keep tests simple and focused.
- Avoid test interdependencies.

## Test documentation

- Document test purpose and expectations in docstrings.
- Include examples of test data and expected outcomes.
- Document any special setup requirements or prerequisites.
- Explain complex test scenarios and edge cases.
- Add comments for non-obvious test logic.
- Document mock behavior and assumptions.

## Test maintenance

- Keep tests up to date with code changes.
- Remove obsolete tests when code is removed.
- Refactor tests when test code becomes complex.
- Use shared test utilities for common operations.
- Keep test code as clean as production code.
- Update tests when fixing bugs.
- Add regression tests for fixed issues.
